{{for|the Italian sparkling wine|Franciacorta (wine)}}
[[File:Franciacorta-vista.jpg|thumb|500px|Panoramic view of Franciacorta from ''Monte Alto'']]
[[File:Erbusco.jpg|thumb|Franciacorta vineyard in [[Erbusco]]]]
The territory of '''Franciacorta''' is a section of the [[Province of Brescia]] in the Italian Region of [[Lombardy]]. Franciacorta extends from Mount Orfano (south of [[Rovato]]) on the southwest area to the shores of [[Lake Iseo]], and from the river [[Oglio]] on the western border to the city of [[Brescia]] in the east. The geography of rolling hills was shaped by glacial action. The soil, [[Moraine|glacial moraines]] consisting of gravel and sand over limestone, drains well, and is ideal for the cultivation of grapes and winemaking. The weather is mild and constant due to its location south of the foothills of the [[Alps]] and the tempering presence of large lakes. To publicize [[enotourism]] the district established a ''Strada del Vino Franciacorta'' on the model of the famed [[German Wine Route]] (''Weinstraße'') in 2001.

The area has been inhabited since Palaeolithic times, with archaeological records left by [[Gaul]]s&mdash; the [[Cenomani (Cisalpine Gaul)|Cenomani]] of ''Brixia'' (modern [[Brescia]]), Romans and [[Lombards]]. The name Franciacorta, attested in 1277, is thought to derive from ''curtes francae'', the fortified courts of the Frankish empire established in the 8th century.

[[Rodengo Saiano|Rodengo]] is home to a [[Cluniac]] foundation, the [[Abbey of St. Nicholas]], which has been inhabited by [[Olivetan]] monks since 1446. Other places of interest include [[Passirano]], with a castle, and [[Provaglio d'Iseo]], with a [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque]] church.

Among the most respected [[Franciacorta wine|wine]] producers of Franciacorta [[sparkling wine|sparkling]] and still wines in the region are [[Berlucchi]], [[Bellavista (vineyard)|Bellavista]] and [[Ca' del Bosco]].  Others include Mosnel, Muratori, Lantieri, Majolini, Ferghettina and Cavalleri.

A local circuit has hosted the [[World RX of Italy]] and the [[NASCAR Whelen Euro Series]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rallycrossrx.com/result/ita/2015|title=Results - 2015 World RX of Italy|publisher=rallycrossrx.com|accessdate=25 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://hometracks.nascar.com/tracks/autodromo-di-franciacorta/|title=Autodromo di Franciacorta|accessdate=25 June 2018}}</ref>

