{{short description|A Precambrian microcontinent that broke away as India and Madagascar separated}} {{other uses|Mauritia}} '''Mauritia''' was a [[Precambrian]] [[Continental fragment|microcontinent]] that broke away as [[Indian plate|India]] and [[Madagascar]] separated some 60 million years ago.<ref name="Torsvik2013">{{cite journal|last1=Torsvik|first1=Trond H.| author1link = Trond Helge Torsvik|first2=Hans |last2=Amundsen |first3=Ebbe H. |last3=Hartz |first4=Fernando |last4=Corfu |first5=Nick |last5=Kusznir |first6=Carmen |last6=Gaina |first7=Pavel V. |last7=Doubrovine |first8=Bernhard |last8=Steinberger |first9=Lewis D. |last9=Ashwal |first10=Bjørn |last10=Jamtveit |date=24 February 2013|title=A Precambrian microcontinent in the Indian Ocean|journal=[[Nature Geoscience]]|url=http://gfzpublic.gfz-potsdam.de/pubman/item/escidoc:246388:1/component/escidoc:246387/19819.pdf|accessdate=5 December 2015|issn=1752-0894|doi=10.1038/ngeo1736}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Natali|last=Anderson|url=http://www.sci-news.com/othersciences/geophysics/article00899.html|title=Geoscientists Discover Continent Hidden Under Lava in Indian Ocean|date=25 February 2013|publisher=Sci-News.com|accessdate=25 February 2013}}</ref><ref name=Nytimes2017-02-03/> Evidence consists of detrital [[zircon]] found in rock (6-million-year-old [[trachyte]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://phys.org/news/2017-01-lost-continent-mauritius.html|title=Researchers confirm the existence of a 'lost continent' under Mauritius|date=31 January 2017 |publisher=[[Phys.org]]|accessdate=3 February 2017}}</ref> [[Detrital zircon geochronology|Analyses of the zircon]] crystals produced dates between 660 and 1,970 million years and are considerably older than the 8.9-million-year-old [[basalt]] that constitutes the oldest formations on the island. The zircons are interpreted to have been brought up from buried [[continental crust]] as fragments [[Entrainment (engineering)|entrained]] as [[xenocryst]]s within the basalt.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nature.com/news/long-lost-continent-found-under-the-indian-ocean-1.12487|title=Long-lost continent found under the Indian Ocean|last=Perkins|first=Sid|date=24 February 2013|work=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]|accessdate=25 February 2013|doi=10.1038/nature.2013.12487}}</ref> Interpretation of a linear northwest–southeast [[gravity anomaly]] indicates the microcontinent may extend<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.com/news/scientists-say-lost-ancient-continent-lies-beneath-island-in-indian-ocean |title=Scientists Say Lost Ancient Continent Lies Beneath Island in Indian Ocean. |publisher= History.com| accessdate=}}</ref> {{convert|1500|km}} from the [[Seychelles]] to [[Mauritius]] roughly parallel to the [[Indian Ocean]] [[oceanic ridge]].<ref>{{cite news |title= Ancient micro-continent under the Indian Ocean identified |url= http://www.spacedaily.com/reports/Ancient_micro_continent_under_the_Indian_Ocean_identified_999.html |publisher= SpaceDaily |date= 7 March 2013 }}</ref>
